la|last2=Bandera|first2=Massimiliano|title=San Lazzaro degli Armeni: l'isola, il monastero, il restauro|date=1999|publisher=Marsilio|location=Venezia|isbn=978-88-317-7422-2|oclc=247889977|language=it}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Bolton|first1=Claire|title=A visit to San Lazzaro|date=1982|publisher=Alembic Press|location=Oxford, England|isbn=|oclc=46689623}}\n*{{cite news|last=Richardson|first=Nigel|title=Oasis in the bedlam of Venice|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/travel/destinations/italy/article2907846.ece|work=[[The Times]]|date=13 February 2011|location=London}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Horne|first=Joseph|title=St. Lazzaro, Venice, and its Armenian Convent|journal=[[The Ladies' Repository]]|date=1872|volume=32|issue=10|page=459|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rJ1EAQAAMAAJ}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pasquin Valery|first=Antoine Claude|authorlink=:fr:Antoine Claude Pasquin|title=Historical, literary, and artistical travels in Italy, a completer and methodical guide for travellers and artists [Voyage en Italie, guide du voyageur et de l'artiste]|date=1839|orig-year=1838|publisher=Baudry|location=Paris|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-iYNAAAAYAAJ 191\u2013192]}}\n*{{cite news|last=Fell|first=Cicely|title=Out of Armenia, Venice|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04w0jxm|agency=[[BBC Radio 4]]|date=31 December 2014}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|San Lazzaro degli Armeni (Venice)}}\n*{{cite web|last=Hovhannisyan|first=Rafael|title=\u054e\u0565\u0576\u0565\u057f\u056b\u056f. \u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580 [Venice. San Lazzaro]|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bEUgWVPmSLg|publisher=[[Public Television of Armenia]]|language=hy|date=24 December 2013}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Geography|Islands|Italy}}\n{{Modern Armenian churches and seminaries}}\n{{Islands of the Venetian Lagoon}}\n{{Armenian diaspora}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:San Lazzaro Degli Armeni}}\n[[Category:Armenian culture]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Venetian Lagoon]]\n[[Category:Christian monasteries established in the 18th century]]\n[[Category:Catholic congregations established in the 18th century]]\n[[Category:Mekhitarist Order]]\n[[Category:Libraries in Venice]]\n[[Category:Eastern Catholicism in Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox islands\n| name             = Isola di San Lazzaro degli Armeni\n| image_name       = [[File:San Lazzaro degli Armeni, Venice aerial photo 2013.jpg|280px]]<br>[[File:Isola di San Lazzaro degli Armeni IMG 9175.jpg|280px]]<br>San Lazzaro from a bird's-eye view and as seen from a boat\n| image_size       = 280px\n| image_caption    = \n| coordinates      = {{coord|45.411979|12.361422|region:IT_type:isle_source:GNS-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n| waterbody        = [[Venetian Lagoon]], [[Adriatic Sea]], [[Mediterranean Sea]]\n| area_ha          = 3\n| area_footnotes   = \n| length_km        = <!-- or |length_m=  -->\n| length_footnotes = \n| width_km         = <!-- or |width_m=  -->\n| width_footnotes  =\n| coastline_km     = <!-- or |coastline_m=  -->\n| coastline_footnotes = \n| Country_heading  = \n| country          = [[Italy]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   = [[Regions of Italy|Region]]\n| country_admin_divisions_1         = [[Veneto]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_2   = [[Provinces of Italy|Province]]\n| country_admin_divisions_2         = [[Province of Venice]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_3   = Commune\n| country_admin_divisions_3         = Venice\n| population       = 17\n| population_as_of = 2015\n| population_footnotes = {{sfn|Levonian Cole|2015b}}\n| ethnic_groups    = [[Armenians]] \n}}\n\n'''San Lazzaro degli Armeni''' ({{IPA-it|san \u02c8laddzaro de\u028e\u028e ar\u02c8m\u025b\u02d0ni}}, {{abbr|[[Literal translation|lit.]]|literally}} \"Saint Lazarus of the Armenians\"; called '''Saint Lazarus Island''' in English sources; {{lang-hy|\u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580|Surp Ghazar }}) is a small island in the [[Venetian Lagoon]] which has been home to the monastery of the [[Mekhitarists]], an [[Armenian Catholic]] congregation, since 1717. It is the primary center of the Mekhitarists, while the [[Mekhitarist Monastery of Vienna]] is their primary abbey.<ref>{{cite news|title=In Historic Move Venice and Vienna Mekhitarist Orders Unite|url=http://asbarez.com/42794/in-historic-move-venice-and-vienna-mekhitarist-orders-unite/|work=[[Asbarez]]|date=24 July 2000}}</ref>\n\nThe islet lies {{convert|2|km|abbr=on}} to the southeast of [[Venice]] proper and west of the [[Lido di Venezia|Lido]] and covers an area of {{convert|3|ha}}. Settled in the 9th century, it was a [[leper colony]] during the Middle Ages, but fell into disuse by the early 18th century. In 1717 San Lazzaro was ceded by the [[Republic of Venice]] to [[Mkhitar Sebastatsi]], an [[Armenians|Armenian]] Catholic monk, who established a monastery with his followers. It has since been the headquarters of the Mekhitarists and, as such, one of the world's prominent centers of [[Armenian culture]] and [[Armenian studies]]. Numerous important publications, such as the first complete dictionary of the Armenian language (1749\u201369) and the first modern history of Armenia (1781\u201386), were made in the island by the monks which made it an early major center of [[Armenian printing]].\n\nSan Lazzaro has been enlarged nearly four times from its original size through land reclamation. It was recognized as an academy by [[Napoleon]] in 1810 when nearly all monasteries of Venice were abolished. A significant episode in its history is [[Lord Byron]]'s visit in 1816\u201317. The island is one of the best known historic sites of the [[Armenian diaspora]]. The monastery has a large collection of books, journals, artifacts, and the third largest collection of Armenian manuscripts (more than 3,000). Over the centuries, dozens of artists, writers, political and religious leaders have visited the island. It has since become a tourist destination.\n\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Venice San Lazzaro location map.png|thumb|A satellite image of the Venetian Lagoon. San Lazzaro ''(circled in red)'' is located southeast of Venice and west of the Lido.]]\n\nSan Lazzaro lies {{convert|2|km|abbr=on}} to the southeast of [[Venice]] proper and west of the [[Lido di Venezia|Lido]].<ref>{{cite web|title=San Lazzaro degli Armeni|url=http://www.turismovenezia.it/Venezia/San-Lazzaro-degli-Armeni-6188.html|website=turismovenezia.it|publisher=Provincia di Venezia|quote=...&nbsp;a circa due chilometri da Venezia.|language=it}}</ref> The islet is rectangular-shaped{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=426-427}} and covers an area of {{convert|3|ha}}.{{sfn|Gordan|2012}}{{sfn|Luther|2011}}<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/> The island is accessible by a [[vaporetto]] from the [[San Zaccaria, Venice|San Zaccaria]] station (Pier B).{{sfn|Gordan|2012}}<ref name=\"Rough Guides\">{{cite book|last1=Belford|first1=Ros|last2=Dunford|first2=Martin|last3=Woolfrey|first3=Celia|title=Italy|date=2003|publisher=[[Rough Guides]]|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=guMWMVFhqzwC&pg=PA332&dq=san+lazzaro+Armeni 332]}}</ref> Some 40,000 people visit the island annually,<ref name=\"168am\"/>{{sfn|Levonian Cole|2015b}} with Italians making up the majority of visitors.{{sfn|Levonian Cole|2015a}}\n\nThe island's official [[Italian language|Italian]] name, San Lazzaro degli Armeni, [[Literal translation|literally translates]] to \"Saint Lazarus of the Armenians\".{{sfn|Gordan|2012}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Valcanover|first=Francesco|title=Museums and Galleries of Venice|contribution=Collection of the Armenian Mekhitarist Fathers, Island of St. Lazarus of the Armenians|date=1965|publisher=Moneta Editore|location=Milan|page=149}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Island of Saint Lazarus of the Armenians|url=http://travel.michelin.com/web/destination/Italy-Venice/tourist_site-Island_of_Saint_Lazarus_of_the_Armenians-Isola_S_Lazzaro_degli_Armeni|publisher=[[Michelin Guide]]}}</ref> It is often referred to in English as ''Saint Lazarus Island''.{{sfn|Gordan|2012}} In [[Armenian language|Armenian]], the island is called \u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580, ''Surb Ghazar'' (\"Saint Lazarus\").{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=426-427}}{{efn|Also [[Romanization of Armenian|romanized]] as ''Surb \u0141azar''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Greenwood|first1=Tim|editor1-last=Johnson|editor1-first=Scott Fitzgerald|title=The Oxford Handbook of Late Antiquity|chapter=Armenia|date=2012|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-533693-1|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=KEYSDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA137&lpg=PA137&dq=venice+Surb+\u0141azar 137]}}</ref> Armenian sources often refer to it specifically as \u054e\u0565\u0576\u0565\u057f\u056b\u056f\u056b \u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580 \u056f\u0572\u0566\u056b, \"Saint Lazarus island of Venice\" ([[Eastern Armenian]]: ''Venetiki Surb Ghazar k(\u0259)ghzi''; [[Western Armenian]]: ''Venedigi Surp Ghazar g(\u0259)ghzi'').}}\n\n===Population===\nThe number of monks, students, and other residents at San Lazzaro has fluctuated throughout history. In 1816, when Byron visited the island, there were some 70 Mekhitarists in San Lazzaro.{{sfn|Gordan|2012}} The number of residents has decreased significantly since. By the early 1840s the island housed 50 monks and students,{{sfn|Russell|1842|p=372}} and some 20 monks in 1960.{{sfn|Morris|1960|p=294}} A ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' writer noted in 1998 that San Lazzaro is still a \"monastic hub of activity,\" although at the time the monastery housed only 10 seminarians and 10 fathers.<ref name=\"Toth\">{{cite news|last=Toth|first=Susan Allen|title=Hidden Venice|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/apr/19/magazine/tm-40664/3|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=19 April 1998|page=3}}</ref> Teresa Levonian Cole wrote in ''[[The Independent]]'' that, as of 2015, 12 [[vardapet]]s (educated monks) and five novices reside in San Lazzaro.{{sfn|Levonian Cole|2015a}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:San Lazzaro 16th century.png|thumb|150px|San Lazzaro in a map dating from the second half of the 16th century.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>]]\n\n===Middle Ages===\nThe recorded history of the island begins in the 9th century. In 810, the [[Republic of Venice]] allocated the island to the abbot of the [[Benedictine]] Monastery of St. Ilario of Fusina. In the 12th century, [[leprosy]] appeared in Venice as a result of trade with the East. Leone Paolini, a local nobleman, transferred the simple hospital of [[San Trovaso]] to the island in 1182.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/> Thus, a [[leper colony]]\u2014hospital for people with leprosy\u2014was established at the island, which was chosen for that purpose due to its relative distance from the principal islands forming the city of Venice. It received its name from [[Rich man and Lazarus|St. Lazarus]], the patron saint of lepers.{{sfn|Langlois|1874|pp=12\u201313}}{{sfn|Gordan|2012}} The church of San Lazzaro was founded in 1348, which is attested by an inscription in [[Blackletter|Gothic script]]. In the same year, the hospital was renovated and its ownership transferred from the Benedictines to the patriarchal [[San Pietro di Castello (church)|cathedral of San Pietro]]. Leprosy declined by the mid-1500s and the island was abandoned by 1601 when only the chaplain and some gardeners remained at the island to grow vegetables. In the second half of the 17th century the island was leased to various religious groups. In 1651 a [[Dominican order]] settled at the island after fleeing from Turkish-occupied Crete. [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] also briefly settled in the island.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/> By the early 18th century only a few crumbling ruins remained in the isle.{{sfn|Langlois|1874|pp=12\u201313}}\n\n===Armenian period===\n[[File:The island of St. Lazarus, when Mechitar was there.png|thumb|\"The island of St. Lazarus, when Mechitar was there.\"{{sfn|Nurikhan|1915|p=[https://archive.org/stream/lifetimesofserva00nuriiala#page/231/mode/1up 231]}}]]\n\n====Establishment====\nIn April 1715, a group of twelve Armenian Catholic monks led by [[Mkhitar Sebastatsi]] (English: Mekhitar of Sebaste, Italian: Mechitar) arrived in Venice from [[Morea]], today known as the [[Peloponnese]] peninsula, following its [[Ottoman\u2013Venetian War (1714\u201318)|invasion by the Ottoman Empire]].{{sfn|Langlois|1874|p=13}} The monks were members of a Catholic order founded by Mkhitar in 1701, in [[Constantinople]], the capital of the [[Ottoman Empire]].{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=426-427}} The order moved to [[Methoni, Messenia|Modone (Methoni)]], on the southern shore of the Peloponnese, in 1703,{{sfn|Langlois|1874|p=20}} after repressions by the Ottoman government and the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]]. In 1712 the order received recognition by [[Pope Clement XI]].{{sfn|Hacikyan|Basmajian|Franchuk|Ouzounian|2005|p=51}} [[Victor Langlois]] wrote that a Venetian admiral and the Venetian governor of Morea, \"sympathizing deeply with the fearful distress of the unfortunate community, yielded to their earnest entreaties for permission to embark on a government vessel which was about to leave for Venice.\"{{sfn|Langlois|1874|p=20}}\n\n[[File:Aivazovsky Mekhitarist Fathers San Lazzaro.jpg|thumb|The Mekhitarist Fathers on San Lazzaro Island (1843) by [[Ivan Aivazovsky]].]]\n\nOn September 8, 1717, on the [[Nativity of Mary|Feast of the Nativity of Mary]],  the [[Venetian Senate]] ceded San Lazzaro to Mkhitar and his companions, who agreed not to rename the island.{{sfn|Nurikhan|1915|p=236}}<ref name=\"sae\"/> He was reminded of the [[Sevanavank|monastery]] on the [[Sevan Island|island]] of [[Lake Sevan]], where he had sought education earlier in his life.{{sfn|Nurikhan|1915|p=237}} Upon acquisition, the monks began works of restoration of existing buildings on the island.<ref name=\"sae\"/> The entire community then relocated to the island on April 1718 when the buildings on San Lazzaro became habitable. Mkhitar himself designed the plan of the monastery, which was completed by 1840.{{sfn|Langlois|1874|p=23}} The monastery originally included 16 cells for monks, which were adjusted from the old hospital. The church's restoration lasted from May to November 1722. Mkhitar died in 1749.{{sfn|Langlois|1874|p=24}} The bell tower was completed a year later, in 1750.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>\n\n[[File:The Island of San Lazzaro and the Armenian Monastery.png|thumb|San Lazzaro circa 1877{{sfn|Yriarte|1880|p=[http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=osu.32435006274781;view=1up;seq=425 302]}}]]\n\n====Later history====\nThe Venetian Republic was disestablished by [[Napoleon]] in 1797. In 1810, he abolished all monastic orders of Venice and the [[Kingdom of Italy (Napoleonic)|Kingdom of Italy]], except that of the Mekhitarists in San Lazzaro.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Flagg|first1=Edmund|authorlink1=Edmund Flagg|title=Venice: The City of the Sea: From the Invasion by Napoleon in 1797 to the Capitulation to Radetzky in 1849, Volume I|date=1853|publisher=[[Charles Scribner's Sons|Charles Scribner]]|location=New York|page=[https://archive.org/details/venicecityseafr01flaggoog/page/n267 <!-- quote=napoleon Venice monasteries. --> 263]|quote=As for convents and monasteries, he suppressed all\u2014that of the Armenians only excepted.}}</ref>{{sfn|Russell|1842|p=372}} The Mekhitarist congregation was left in peace, according to some sources, due to the intercession of [[Roustam Raza]], Napoleon's [[Mamluk]] bodyguard of Armenian origin.<ref name=\"Russel\">{{cite journal|last=Russel|first=C.|title=Armenia and the Armenians|journal=[[Church of England Newspaper|The Church of England Magazine]]|date=19 February 1870|volume=LXVIII|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=JScFAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA107 107]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Buckley|first=Jonathan|title=The Rough Guide to Venice & the Veneto|year=2010|publisher=[[Rough Guides]]|location=London|isbn=978-1-84836-870-5|page=226|edition=8th}}</ref> Napoleon signed a decree, dated August 27, 1810, which declared that the congregation may continue to exist as an academy.<ref name=\"Napoleon\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Le comunita' religiose nelle isole (Religious communities in the islands)|url=http://www.turismo.provincia.venezia.it/turismoambientale/cd_1/itinerari/comunitareligiose/comunita.html|website=turismo.provincia.venezia.it|publisher=[[Metropolitan City of Venice|Citt\u00e0 metropolitana di Venezia]]|language=it|quote=Pur trattandosi di una comunit\u00e0 religiosa, questa non venne soppressa da Napoleone che la consider\u00f2 un'accademia letteraria probabilmente in rapporto all'importante attivit\u00e0 editoriale svolta dai monaci.}}</ref> Since then, San Lazzaro is also known as an academy and sometimes referred to in [[Latin]] as ''Academia Armena Sancti Lazari''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Monast\u00e8re m\u00e9khitariste de Saint-Lazare <Venise, Italie> (1717 - )|url=https://thesaurus.cerl.org/record/cnc00020417|publisher=[[Consortium of European Research Libraries]]}}</ref>\n\nThe monastery has been enlarged significantly through [[land reclamation]] four time since the 19th century. First, in 1815, the Mekhitarists were permitted by Austrian Emperor [[Francis II, Holy Roman Emperor|Francis I]] to expand the island. The area north of the island was filled which doubled its area from 7,900m\u00b2 to 13,700&nbsp;m\u00b2. In 1836, a boundary wall around the island's newly reclaimed area was built. The channel of the boathouse was filled in 1912 and it was moved to the far western corner. The shoreline was straightened. These adjustments increased its area to 16,970&nbsp;m\u00b2. San Lazzaro's latest major enlargement occurred in post-[[World War II]] period. Between 1947 and 1949, the island was expanded on the southeast and the southwest. The island now has an area of 30,000&nbsp;m\u00b2 or 3 hectares.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>{{sfn|Luther|2011}}\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" caption=\"Gradual expansion of San Lazzaro\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:San Lazzaro degli Armeni 1717.png|The island when Armenian monks arrived, 1717\nFile:San Lazzaro degli Armeni 1789.png|The construction of the monastic complex by Mkhitar (1740) and the printing house (1789).\nFile:San Lazzaro degli Armeni 1818.png|The enlargement on the northern side of the island (1818) and the wing of the new printing house (1823\u201325).\nFile:San Lazzaro degli Armeni plan.png|Enlargement of the southern side of the island (1947\u201349)\n</gallery>\n\n[[File:San Lazzaro degli Armeni 1934.png|thumb|A 1934 photo of the island by Swiss aviator [[Walter Mittelholzer]].]]\n\n====20th century and beyond====\nThe island was heavily affected by the unprecedented [[1966 Venice flood|''acqua alta'' of November 4, 1966]]. The flooded sea water entered the main church and flooded the enclosed garden for around 12 hours. The library and the manuscript depository were not affected by the flood and none of the churchmen suffered injuries.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Editorial |title=\u0548\u0572\u0578\u0572\u0578\u0582\u0574 \u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580 \u057e\u0561\u0576\u0584\u0578\u0582\u0574 |journal=[[Etchmiadzin (magazine)|Etchmiadzin]] |date=1967 |volume=23 |issue=1-2 |url=http://echmiadzin.asj-oa.am/5457/ |publisher=[[Mother See of Holy Etchmiadzin]] |language=hy}}</ref> A fire broke out on the night of December 8, 1975, which partially destroyed the library and damaged the southern side of the church, and destroyed two [[Gaspare Diziani]] paintings.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>\n\nBetween 2002 and 2004, an extensive restoration of the monastery's structures was carried out by the [[:it:Magistrato alle acque|Magistrato alle acque]] under the coordination of [[:it:Consorzio Venezia Nuova|Consorzio Venezia Nuova]], an agency of the [[Ministry of Infrastructure and Transport (Italy)|Italian Ministry of Infrastructure and Transport]]. It included restoration of the island's shores and its walls and the boathouse.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>\n\nSan Lazzaro hosted the pavilion of Armenia during the 56th [[Venice Biennale]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGarry|first1=Kevin|title=Highlights From the 56th Venice Biennale|url=http://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/05/12/56th-venice-biennale-highlights/?_r=0|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=12 May 2015}}</ref> The exhibition, dedicated to the [[100th anniversary of the Armenian Genocide]] and curated by [[Adelina von F\u00fcrstenberg|Adelina C\u00fcberyan von Furstenberg]], won the Golden Lion award in the national participation category.<ref>{{cite web|title=Republic of Armenia Pavilion at the 56th Venice Biennale|url=https://www.artsy.net/article/artsy-editorial-republic-of-armenia-pavilion-at-the-56th-venice|website=[[Artsy (website)|artsy.net]]|date=18 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Golden Lions for Armenia, Adrian Piper at Venice Biennale|url=http://www.dw.com/en/golden-lions-for-armenia-adrian-piper-at-venice-biennale/a-18441763|agency=[[Deutsche Welle]]|date=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nSan Lazzaro was affected by the November 13, 2019 flood.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0540\u0565\u0572\u0565\u0572\u057e\u0565\u056c \u0567 \u054e\u0565\u0576\u0565\u057f\u056b\u056f\u056b \u057d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580 \u056f\u0572\u0566\u056b\u0576 |url=https://www.facebook.com/lurer.1tv/videos/465990320708599/?v=465990320708599 |publisher=News on [[Public Television Company of Armenia|First Channel]] |language=hy |date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Monastery==\n[[File:St-lazare-cour.jpg|thumb|The cloister of the monastery with the onion-shaped bell tower]]\n\nSan Lazzaro is entirely occupied by the Mekhitarist monastery of San Lazzaro, which is the headquarters of the [[Armenian Catholic Church|Armenian Catholic]] [[Mekhitarists|Mekhitarist Congregation]]. The monastery is known in Armenian as \u0544\u056d\u056b\u0569\u0561\u0580\u0565\u0561\u0576 \u0544\u0561\u0575\u0580\u0561\u057e\u0561\u0576\u0584, ''M(\u0259)khitarian Mayravank''', which literally translates to the \"Mekhitarist Mother Monastery\" and in Italian as ''Monastero Mechitarista''.<ref name=\"turismovenezia\"/> The monastery currently contains a church with a bell tower, residential quarters, library, museums, picture gallery, manuscript repository, printing plant, sundry teaching and research facilities, gardens,{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=426-427}} a bronze statue of Mkhitar erected by Antonio Baggio in 1962,<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/> an [[Armenian Genocide]] memorial erected in the 1960s,<ref>{{cite web|title=Memorial on Saint Lazarus Island, Venice, Italy|url=http://www.armenian-genocide.org/Memorial.98/current_category.68/memorials_detail.html|publisher=[[Armenian National Institute]]}}</ref> and a 14th-century basalt ''[[khachkar]]'' (cross stone) donated by the Soviet Armenian government in 1987.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>\n\nThe [[cloister]] of the monastery consists of a colonnade of 42 columns in the [[Doric order]]. There is a 15th-century [[water well]] in the center of the cloister, which is surrounded by trees and shrubs. A [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]] and [[Early Christian art and architecture|early Christian]] inscriptions, a first century headless statue of a Roman noble from [[Aquileia]] and other artifacts were found there.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>\n\nThe [[bell tower]] with an [[onion dome]] was completed in 1750.{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=426-427}} It is not attached to the church and stands alone near the northern side of the church.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>\n\n===The church===\n[[File:San Lazzaro degli Armeni church interior2.jpg|thumb|The interior of the church]]\n\nThe church of San Lazzaro, although renovated several times through centuries, retains the 14th century pointed arch style. The church was restored extensively by Mkhitar in 1722, five years after the settlement of Armenian monks. He completely rebuilt the altar. Its apse was extended in 1899 primarily with an addition of neo-Gothic elements.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/> The church has a [[neo-Gothic]] interior.{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=426-427}} It is three-[[nave]]d, supported by 6 red marble columns.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/> The main altar is in [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]] style. The three main windows of the altar's apse have [[stained glass]] which depict from left to right: [[Isaac of Armenia|Sahak Patriarch]], Saint Lazarus, and [[Mesrop Mashtots]]. In the church, there are frescoes and paintings by [[Antonio Ermolao Paoletti]] depicting [[Saint Peter]], [[Saint Paul]], [[John the Baptist]] and [[Saint Stephen]]. The tomb of Mkhitar is located in the front of the altar.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>\n\nBesides the main altar, there are four other altars dedicated to the Holy Cross, St. [[Gregory the Illuminator]], [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Mary]], and [[Anthony the Great]]. All built in the period of 1735\u201338 by Mkhitar. They are all adorned by pieces of works, mainly by Venetian artists. The St. Gregory [[altarpiece]] by [[No\u00e8 Bordignon]] depicts the saint performing the baptism of the Armenian king [[Tiridates III of Armenia|Tiridates III]]. The altarpiece dedicated to the mother of Jesus depicts the [[Nativity of Mary]] by [[Domenico Maggiotto]]. The altarpiece of St. Anthony by [[Francesco Zugno]] depicts the founder of the Oriental monasticism who inspired Mkhitar.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>\n\n;Paintings \nWithin the church, there are paintings of Armenian saints by Paoletti created in 1901: Ghevond, [[Hripsime]], Nerses of Lambron, [[St. Nerses I|Nerses the Great]], Sandukht, [[Vardan Mamikonian|Vardan]], [[Gregory of Narek]], [[Nerses IV the Gracious|Nerses Shnorhali]]. Other significant paintings include Madonna with Child by [[Palma il Giovane]] (Jacopo Negretti), the baptism of king Tiridates III by St. Gregory the Illuminator by [[:hy:\u0540\u0578\u057e\u0570\u0561\u0576\u0576\u0565\u057d \u054a\u0561\u057f\u056f\u0565\u0580\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0576|Hovhannes Patkerahan]] (1720), [[Assumption of Mary]] by [[Jacopo Bassano]], [[Annunciation]] and [[Virgin of Mercy|Mother of Mercy]] by [[Matteo Cesa]], the [[Genesis flood narrative|Flood]] by [[Leandro Bassano]], [[Flight into Egypt]] by [[Marco Basaiti]], Annunciation by [[Bernardo Strozzi]], St. [[Thecla]] and Sts. Peter and Paul by [[Girolamo da Santacroce]], ''Moses Saved from the Waters'' and [[Raphael (archangel)|Archangel Raphael]] by [[Luca Carlevarijs]].<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>\n\n===Gardens===\nThe gardens of the monastery have been admired by many visitors.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Clement|first1=Clara Erskine|authorlink1=Clara Erskine Clement|title=The Queen of the Adriatic or Venice, Mediaeval and Modern|date=1893|publisher=Estes and Lauriat|location=Boston|page=[https://archive.org/stream/queenofadriatic00wateiala#page/312/mode/2up 312]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Macfarlane|first=Charles|authorlink=Charles Macfarlane|title=The Armenians: A Tale of Constantinople, Volume 1|date=1830|publisher=Carey and Lea|location=Philadelphia|page=[https://archive.org/details/armeniansatalec00macfgoog/page/n260 254]|quote=San Lazaro is about the middle size, and adorned with a pretty garden&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref name=\"Garrett\"/><ref name=\"Carswell\"/> \"The island&nbsp;... with its flower and fruit gardens, is so well kept that an excursion to San Lazzaro is a favourite one with all visitors to Venice,\" noted one visitor in 1905.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Robertson|first1=Alexander|title=The Roman Catholic Church in Italy|date=1905|publisher=Morgan and Scott|page=[https://archive.org/details/romancatholicch00robegoog/page/n198 <!-- quote=flower and fruit gardens. --> 186]}}</ref>  Irish botanist [[Edith Blake]] wrote: \"The garden in the centre of the cloisters was gay with flowers, and there was a calm, peaceful air of repose over the whole place.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Blake|first1=Edith Osborne|authorlink1=Edith Blake|title=Twelve Months in Southern Europe|date=1876|publisher=[[Chapman & Hall]]|location=London|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=Xw5HAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA144 144]}}</ref>\n\nThe monks at San Lazzaro make jam from the roses grown in the gardens. The jam, called ''[[:it:Vartanush|Vartanush]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Maggio: le rose|url=http://d.repubblica.it/argomenti/2012/05/11/news/ricetta_del_mese-1007632/|work=[[la Repubblica]]|date=11 May 2012|language=it|quote=Mentre di origine armena \u00e8 la \"vartanush\", la marmellata di rose che in Italia viene prodotta a Venezia, nell'Isola di San Lazzaro degli Armeni dai monaci Mechitaristi.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Isola di San Lazzaro degli Armeni|url=http://www.italianbotanicalheritage.com/it/scheda.php?struttura=814|publisher=Italian Botanical Heritage|language=it|quote=Una tecnica secolare ne imprigiona i profumi nella Vartanush, la marmellata di petali di rose che, tradizionalmente, vengono colti al sorgere del sole.}}</ref>{{efn|[[Western Armenian]] pronunciation of \u057e\u0561\u0580\u0564\u0561\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0577, ''vardanush'' literally translating to \"sweet rose\"; also a female given name.}} is made from rose petal around May, when the roses are in full bloom. Besides rose petal, it contains white caster sugar, water, and lemon juice.<ref>{{cite web|last=Davies|first=Emiko|title=Rose petal Jam from a Venetian monastery|url=http://www.emikodavies.com/blog/rose-petal-jam/|website=emikodavies.com|date=10 May 2011}}</ref> Around five thousand jars of jam are made and sold in the gift shop in the island. Monks also eat it for breakfast.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gora|first=Sasha|title=San Lazzaro degli Armeni \u2013 Where Monks Make Rose Petal Jam in Venice, Italy|url=http://honestcooking.com/where-monks-make-rose-petal-jam-in-venice-italy-story/|website=Honest Cooking|date=8 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\n===Library===\n[[File:Le mus\u00e9e de San Lazzaro degli Armeni (lagune de Venise).jpg|thumb|The library room]]\n\nThe library contains 150,000 to 200,000{{efn|150,000,{{sfn|Gordan|2012}}{{sfn|Saryan|2011|p=1}}{{sfn|Luther|2011}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mayes|first=Frances|title=The Enduring Mystique of the Venetian Lagoon|journal=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]]|date=23 December 2015|url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/mystique-venice-lagoon-180956871/#WmmcLy5L4WSVy8YZ.99|quote=What the monastery is most known for is the library of glass-fronted cases holding some of the monks' 150,000 volumes&nbsp;...}}</ref> 170,000,<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/> 200,000.{{sfn|Levonian Cole|2015a}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dunglas|first1=Dominique|title=La possibilit\u00e9 des \u00eeles [The possibility of islands]|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/voyages/la-possibilite-des-iles-20-04-2011-1323932_44.php|work=[[Le Point]]|date=20 April 2011|language=fr|quote=San Lazzaro degli Armeni. La biblioth\u00e8que du monast\u00e8re, o\u00f9 vivent une poign\u00e9e de moines arm\u00e9niens, ne compte pas moins de 200 000 livres pr\u00e9cieux&nbsp;...}}</ref>}} printed books in Armenian, as well as European and Oriental languages. Some 30,000 European books printed before 1800 are kept at the library.{{sfn|Levonian Cole|2015b}} The entire collection includes books on the arts, the sciences, history, natural history, diverse classical texts, literary criticism, major encyclopedias and other reference books.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>\n\nThe floor of the library is decorated in a Venetian style. Its ceiling, partially destroyed in the 1975 fire, was painted by [[Francesco Zugno]] and depicts [[Catherine of Alexandria]], the four fathers of the Latin Church ([[Ambrose]], [[Augustine of Hippo|Augustine]], [[Jerome]], [[Pope Gregory I|St. Gregory the Great]]), and fathers of the Armenian Church. A chalk sculpture of [[Napoleon II]] by [[Antonio Canova]] is preserved in a glass cabinet in the library. A sculpture of [[Pope Gregory XVI]] by [[Giuseppe De Fabris]], presented to the Mekhitarists by the Pope himself, is also kept at the room.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>{{sfn|Morris|1960|p=294}}\n\n===Manuscripts===\n[[File:Gospel, 862.jpg|thumb|A page from the 9th century Gospel of Queen Mlke]]\nThe Mekhitarists regard the collection of manuscripts the greatest treasure of San Lazzaro. During the 19th century, Mekhitarist monks extracted from these manuscripts and published some previously unpublished pieces of Armenian and non-Armenian literature.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/> According to the magazine of the [[Church of England]], by 1870, San Lazzaro had the second largest collection of Armenian manuscripts after [[Etchmiadzin Cathedral|Etchmiadzin]] having some 1,200 manuscripts in possession.<ref name=\"Russel\"/> The exact current number of manuscripts preserved at San Lazzaro is unknown. According to [[Bernard Coulie]] the number is around 3,000,{{sfn|Coulie|2014|p=26}} which comprises some 10% of all extant Armenian manuscripts.{{sfn|Coulie|2014|p=23}} According to the Mekhitarist Congregation website the monastery contains 4,500 Armenian manuscripts.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>{{sfn|Levonian Cole|2015b}} ''[[Armenian Weekly]]'' writer Levon Saryan noted that the manuscript collection of San Lazzaro consists of over 3,000 complete volumes and about 2,000 fragments.{{sfn|Saryan|2011|p=3}} San Lazzaro is usually ranked as the third largest collection of Armenian manuscripts in the world after the [[Matenadaran]] in [[Yerevan]], Armenia and the [[Armenian Patriarchate of Jerusalem]].{{sfn|Coulie|2014|p=26}}{{efn|Matenadaran holds 11,000 Armenian manuscripts in the strict sense{{sfn|Coulie|2014|p=26}} and 17,000 in total.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mesrop Mashtots Matenadaran|url=http://www.armenianheritage.org/en/monument/Matenadaran/469|website=armenianheritage.org|publisher=Armenian Monuments Awareness Project}}</ref> The Armenian Patriarchate of Jerusalem has 3,890 inventoried manuscripts.{{sfn|Coulie|2014|p=26}} }} The manuscript collection is kept in the [[Rotunda (architecture)|rotunda]]-shaped tower, called the Manuscript Room (manuscript repository). Its construction was funded by Cairo-based Armenian antiques dealer Boghos Ispenian and was designed by his son Andon Ispenian. It was inaugurated in 1970 in attendance of Catholicos [[Vasken I]].<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>{{sfn|Luther|2011}}\n\nThe earliest manuscripts preserved at the repository date to the eighth century.{{sfn|Mesrobian|1973|p=33}}<ref name=\"Fodor's\"/> Among its notable manuscripts are the 9th century Gospel of Queen Mlke ([[:hy:\u0544\u056c\u0584\u0565 \u0569\u0561\u0563\u0578\u0582\u0570\u0578\u0582 \u0531\u057e\u0565\u057f\u0561\u0580\u0561\u0576|\u0544\u056c\u0584\u0565 \u0569\u0561\u0563\u0578\u0582\u0570\u0578\u0582 \u0531\u057e\u0565\u057f\u0561\u0580\u0561\u0576]]),<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kouymjian |first1=Dickran |authorlink1=Dickran Kouymjian |title=Index of Armenian Art: Queen Mlk'e Gospel |url=http://armenianstudies.csufresno.edu/iaa_miniatures/manuscript.aspx?ms=V1144G |website=armenianstudies.csufresno.edu |publisher=[[California State University, Fresno]] |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613092227/http://armenianstudies.csufresno.edu/iaa_miniatures/manuscript.aspx?ms=V1144G |archivedate=2010-06-13 }}</ref> the early 11th century [[Edirne|Adrianopolis]] Gospel; the ''Life of Alexander the Great'', an Armenian translation of a 5th-century Greek version by [[Callisthenes|Pseudo-Callistene]]; the Gospels of Gladzor (dated 1307). In 1976\u201379 some 300 manuscripts were donated by Harutiun Kurdian, for which new display cases were added.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/> It holds one of the ten<ref>{{cite news|last=Trvnats|first=Anush|title=\u0539\u0578\u0582\u0565\u0580 \u0535\u0582 \u0553\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0565\u0580` \u0540\u0561\u0575 \u0533\u0580\u0561\u057f\u057a\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0565\u0561\u0576 \u054a\u0561\u057f\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0569\u056b\u0582\u0576\u056b\u0581 [Number and facts from the history of Armenian printing]|url=http://www.aztagdaily.com/archives/63548|work=[[Aztag]]|date=28 April 2012|language=hy|quote=\u00ab\u0548\u0582\u0580\u0562\u0561\u0569\u0561\u0563\u0580\u0584\u056b\u00bb \u0561\u057c\u0561\u057b\u056b\u0576 \u0570\u0580\u0561\u057f\u0561\u0580\u0561\u056f\u0578\u0582\u0569\u056b\u0582\u0576\u056b\u0581 \u0561\u0577\u056d\u0561\u0580\u0570\u0578\u0582\u0574 \u057a\u0561\u0570\u057a\u0561\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0565\u056c \u0567 10 \u0585\u0580\u056b\u0576\u0561\u056f}}</ref> extant copies of ''[[Urbatagirk]]'', the first-ever Armenian book printed by [[Hakob Meghapart]] in Venice in 1512.<ref>{{cite news|last=Yapoudjian|first=Hagop|title=\u0544\u057f\u0578\u0580\u0578\u0582\u0574\u0576\u0565\u0580 \u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580 \u0531\u0575\u0581\u0565\u056c\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0565\u0561\u0576 \u0544\u0568 \u0531\u057c\u056b\u0569\u0578\u057e [Thoughts on visit to San Lazzaro]|url=http://www.aztagdaily.com/archives/154959|work=[[Aztag]]|date=14 October 2013|language=hy}}</ref> Furthermore, 44 Armenian prayer scrolls (''hmayil'') are preserved at the repository.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ghazaryan |first1=Davit|title=\u053f\u056b\u057a\u0580\u056b\u0561\u0576\u0578\u057d \u0570\u0561\u0575\u0580\u0561\u057a\u0565\u057f\u0568 \u0587 \u0540\u0578\u0582\u057d\u057f\u056b\u0561\u0576\u0565 \u056f\u0578\u0582\u0575\u057d\u0568 15-16-\u0580\u0564 \u0564\u0561\u0580\u0565\u0580\u056b \u056a\u0561\u057a\u0561\u057e\u0565\u0576\u0561\u0571\u0587 \u0570\u0574\u0561\u0575\u056b\u056c\u0576\u0565\u0580\u056b \u0563\u0565\u0572\u0561\u0580\u057e\u0565\u057d\u057f\u0561\u056f\u0561\u0576 \u0570\u0561\u0580\u0564\u0561\u0580\u0561\u0576\u0584\u0578\u0582\u0574 [Patriarch Kyprianos and Justinia the virgin in the artistic decoration of 15th-16th century ribbon-like hmayils]|journal=[[Matenadaran|Banber Matenadarani]] |date=2014 |page=244 |url=http://www.matenadaran.am/ftp/data/Banber20/17.D.Ghazaryan.pdf |language=hy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150127040626/http://www.matenadaran.am/ftp/data/Banber20/17.D.Ghazaryan.pdf |archivedate=January 27, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Armenian museum===\n[[File:Le mus\u00e9e de San Lazzaro degli Armeni (lagune de Venise) (1620726414).jpg|thumb|The Armenian museum. The painting in the middle is [[Ivan Aivazovsky]]'s ''Chaos'' (1841).]] \nThe Armenian museum was designed by Venetian architect Giovanni Rossi and completed in 1867. Seriously damaged by a 1975 fire, it was restored in its present from by Manouk Manoukian. It formerly served as the library of Armenian manuscripts and publications. The museum now houses items related to Armenian history and art, inducing helmets and bronze belts from the [[Urartu|Urartian]] period; the [[:File:The sword of Leon 5th (the last armenian king of Cilicia).jpg|sword]] of [[Leo V, King of Armenia|Leo V]], the last [[Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia|Armenian King of Cilicia]], forged in [[Sis (ancient city)|Sis]] in 1366;{{sfn|Levonian Cole|2015a}} Armenian ceramics from [[K\u00fctahya]]; coins, stamps and a passport issued by the 1918\u201320 [[First Republic of Armenia]]. Numerous Armenian religious objects of art from the 16th to 18th centuries are on display. A bas-relief in [[agate]] from the medieval Armenian capital of [[Ani]] and a curtain formerly hang at the monastery of [[Ad\u0131r Island|Lim Island]] on [[Lake Van]] are also on display, along with several paintings by Russian-Armenian marine artist [[Ivan Aivazovsky]], including depictions of [[Mount Ararat]] and [[Niagara Falls]]. His [[Genesis creation narrative|Biblical creation]]-themed painting ''[[:File:Aivazovsky Chaos 1841.jpg|Chaos]]'' (1841) was donated to the congregation by [[Pope Leo XIII]] in 1901. The [[death mask]] of [[Komitas]], the musicologist who established the Armenian national school of music, is also on display in the museum.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/> Also on display is one of the most ancient swords ever found, originating from Anatolia and dating to the 3rd Millennium B.C.E.<ref name=\"Anatolian sword\">{{cite news |title='Unbelievable' discovery of a 5,000-year-old sword is made by an archaeology student at a Venetian monastery |url=https://www.cnn.com/style/article/5000-year-old-sword-discovered-in-italy-trnd/index.html |work=cnn.com|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Student discovers 5,000-year-old sword hidden in Venetian monastery |url=https://www.livescience.com/ancient-anatolian-sword-in-venetian-monastery.html |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> This sword are comparable in composition, style and date to the [[Melid#Early_swords|Melid early swords]].\n\n===Oriental museum===\n[[File:San Lazzaro degli Armeni Egyptian mummy.jpg|thumb|The Egyptian mummy]]\n\nOriental and Egyptian publications and artifacts are held in what is called the \"Lord Byron Room\", because it is where he studied Armenian language and culture during his visit to San Lazzaro. It was originally the manuscript room.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/> Its most notable item is the [[Mummy#Egyptian mummies|Egyptian mummy]], sent to San Lazzaro in 1825 by [[Boghos Yousefian|Boghos Bey Yusufian]], an Egyptian minister of Armenian origin. It is attributed to Namenkhet Amun, a priest at the [[Precinct of Amun-Re|Amon Temple]] in [[Karnak]], and has been [[Radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon dated]] to 450\u2013430 BC ([[late period of ancient Egypt]]).<ref>{{cite journal|last=Huchet|first=Jean-Bernard|title=Archaeoentomological study of the insect remains found within the mummy of Namenkhet Amun (San Lazzaro Armenian Monastery, Venice/Italy)|journal=Advances in Egyptology|date=2010|issue=1|pages=59\u201380|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/236176273}}</ref> The collection also includes  [[Etruscan vase painting|Etruscan vases]], Chinese antiques,<ref name=\"rfi\"/> a princely Indian throne with ivory inlay work, and a rare [[papyrus]] in 12 segments in [[Pali]] of a Buddhist ritual, with bustrophedic writing in red lacquer on gold leaf brought from Madras by a Russian-Armenian archaeologist, who discovered it in a temple in 1830.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>\n\n===Paintings===\nAmong the art works on display at the monastery corridors are charcoal drawings by [[Edgar Chahine]], landscapes by [[Martiros Saryan]], [[Mount Ararat]] by [[Gevorg Bashinjaghian]], a marine painting by [[Charles Garabed Atamian]] and a collage by [[Sergei Parajanov]], a [[triptych]] by [[Francesco Zugno]] depicting the baptism of King [[Tiridates III of Armenia|Tiridates III]] by [[Gregory the Illuminator]], various paintings by [[Luigi Querena]], [[Binding of Isaac]] by [[Francesco Hayez]], and others.<ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/>\n\n==Publishing house ==\nA publishing house was established at the island in 1789.<ref name=\"Mouradyan\"/><ref name=\"mechitar.com\"/> It was closed down in 1991, however, the Mekhitarists of San Lazzaro continue publication through their publishing house, ''Casa Editrice Armena''.{{sfn|Gordan|2012}}<ref name=\"Mouradyan\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u0410\u0440\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u044f\u043b \u0430\u0431\u0431\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043c\u0445\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432 [President of Armenia received abbot of Mekhitarist brotherhood]|url=https://regnum.ru/news/polit/1128430.html|agency=[[REGNUM News Agency]]|date=23 February 2009|language=ru|quote=\u0422\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f \u043e\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430, \u0433\u0434\u0435 \u043a\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0447\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043a\u043d\u0438\u0433\u0438 \u043d\u0430 36 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u0445, \u0431\u044b\u043b\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0442\u0430 \u0432 1991 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443.}}</ref> Until the early 20th century, a number of important publications were made on the island. [[Khachig T\u00f6l\u00f6lyan]] wrote of the role the Mekhitarists and their publications:<ref name=\"T\u00f6l\u00f6lyan\"/>\n{{quote frame|With astonishing foresight and energy, the scholar-monks of this diasporic enclave set out to accomplish what [Armenian scholar Marc Nichanian] has described as a totalizing project, a cultural program of research and publication that imagined Armenian life and culture as lamentably fragmented, and launched an effort to equip both the deprived homeland population and the artisans and merchants of the diaspora with the wherewithal of a national culture on the European model.}} \nThe publications of the Mekhitarists, both in San Lazzaro and Vienna, contributed greatly to the refinement of [[Literary language|literary]] [[Western Armenian]].{{sfn|Hacikyan|Basmajian|Franchuk|Ouzounian|2005|p=55}} The San Lazzaro branch became particularly noted in the fields of history, the arts, and literature influenced by the Italian penchant for the arts.{{sfn|Hacikyan|Basmajian|Franchuk|Ouzounian|2005|p=52}} The publishing house printed books in dozens of languages, which included themes such as theology, history, linguistics, literature, natural sciences, and economics. They also published textbooks and translations from European languages and editions of classics.<ref name=\"T\u00f6l\u00f6lyan\"/>\n\n===Significant publications ===\n{{quote box\n| width  = 26%\n| align  = right\n| quote  = \"Texts of most of the Armenian fathers and historians have been printed by the Mechitharists of San Lazaro, Venice, and are readily procurable at their convent.\"\n| source = &nbsp;\u2014[[Frederick Cornwallis Conybeare|F. C. Conybeare]], 1911<ref>{{cite book |last1=Conybeare |first1=F. C. |authorlink1=Frederick Cornwallis Conybeare |title=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |date=1911 |edition=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition|11th]] |chapter=Armenian Language and Literature|title-link=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica }}</ref>\n}}\n\nAmong its publications, the most significant work is the two-volume dictionary of [[Classical Armenian]]: \u0532\u0561\u057c\u0563\u056b\u0580\u0584 \u0540\u0561\u0575\u056f\u0561\u0566\u0565\u0561\u0576 \u053c\u0565\u0566\u0578\u0582\u056b ''Ba\u1e5bgirk\u02bb haykazean lezui'' (''Dictionary of the Armenian Language'', 1749\u201369), which made Armenian the sixth language (after Latin, Greek, French, Italian, and Spanish) to have such a complete dictionary.{{sfn|Suny|1993|p=56}} Its expanded and improved edition, \u0546\u0578\u0580 \u0532\u0561\u057c\u0563\u056b\u0580\u0584 \u0540\u0561\u0575\u056f\u0561\u0566\u0565\u0561\u0576 \u053c\u0565\u0566\u0578\u0582\u056b, ''Nor ba\u1e5bgirk\u02bb haykazean lezui'' (''New Dictionary of the Armenian Language'', 1836\u201337), is considered a monumental achievement and remains unsurpassed.{{sfn|Suny|1993|p=251}}<ref name=\"Mathews\"/><ref name=\"Mouradyan\"/> [[Mikayel Chamchian]] published the first modern history of Armenia in three volumes (1781\u201386).{{sfn|Suny|1993|pp=57, 252}} [[Ronald Grigor Suny]] argues that these publications laid the foundations for the emergence of secular Armenian nationalism.{{sfn|Suny|1993|p=6}} Beginning in 1800 a periodical journal has been published at the island. ''[[Bazmavep]]'', a literary, historical and scientific journal, was established in 1843 and continues to be published to this day.<ref>{{cite news|last=Conway Morris|first=Roderick|title=The Key to Armenia's Survival|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=980DEEDA1F3EF937A15751C0A9649D8B63|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=24 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Mouradyan\"/>\n\n==Role in Armenian history==\n{{quote box\n| width  = 20%\n| align  = right\n| quote  = An Armenian island in the foreign waters,<br />You rekindle the old light of Armenia&nbsp;...<br />Outside the homeland, for the sake of the homeland.\n| source = &nbsp;\u2014[[Hovhannes Shiraz]]'s poem on San Lazzaro<ref>\u0555\u057f\u0561\u0580 \u057b\u0580\u0565\u0580\u0578\u0582\u0574 \u0570\u0561\u0575\u0561\u0581\u0565\u0561\u056c \u053f\u0572\u0566\u056b / \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0578\u0581 \u0570\u056b\u0576 \u056c\u0578\u0582\u0575\u057d\u0576 \u0567 \u0584\u0565\u0566\u0576\u0578\u057e \u0576\u0578\u0580\u0561\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0574&nbsp;... / \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0580\u0565\u0576\u056b\u0584\u056b\u0581 \u0564\u0578\u0582\u0580\u057d\u055d \u0570\u0561\u0575\u0580\u0565\u0576\u0565\u0561\u0581 \u0570\u0561\u0574\u0561\u0580: {{cite web|title=\u0540\u0561\u0575\u0565\u0580\u0576 \u053b\u057f\u0561\u056c\u056b\u0561\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0574 [Armenians in Italy]|url=http://italy.mfa.am/hy/community-overview-it/|website=italy.mfa.am|publisher=Embassy of Armenia to Italy|language=hy}}</ref>}}\n\nSan Lazzaro has a great historical significance to Armenians and has been described as a \"little Armenia.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Armenia Wins Venice Biennale 2015 Golden Lion Award|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2015/05/14/armenia-venice-biennale-2015/|work=[[Armenian Weekly]]|date=14 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=5th Annual Conference of the Forum of Armenian Associations of Europe Venice, Italy|url=http://faaeurope.ofirme.sk/?run=content&id=4794&lang=sk|publisher=Forum of Armenian Associations of Europe|date=6\u20139 June 2003|quote=The city, which covers more than 200 islands, has a little Armenia in it; Armenian cultural and educational center Saint Ghazar}}</ref><ref>Catholicos [[Karekin II]], the head of the Armenian Apostolic Church, said during his 2008 to the island that San Lazzaro is \"a little Armenia thousands of kilometers away from Armenia.\" {{cite journal|title=\u0546.\u054d.\u0555.\u054f.\u054f. \u0533\u0561\u0580\u0565\u0563\u056b\u0576 \u0532 \u0531\u0574\u0565\u0576\u0561\u0575\u0576 \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0578\u0581 \u053f\u0561\u0569\u0578\u0572\u056b\u056f\u0578\u057d\u056b \u056d\u0578\u057d\u0584\u0568 \u0544\u056d\u056b\u0569\u0561\u0580\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0574\u056b\u0561\u0562\u0561\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576\u0568 \u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580 \u056f\u0572\u0566\u0578\u0582\u0574 [Visit of Catholicos Karekin II to the Mekhitarist Congregation at San Lazzaro island] |journal=[[Etchmiadzin (magazine)|Etchmiadzin]] |date=May 2008 |issue=5 |page=28 |url=http://tert.nla.am/archive/HGG%20AMSAGIR/echmiadzin-vagharshapat/2008/2008(5).pdf |language=hy |quote=\u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580\u0568 \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u056b\u0581 \u0570\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580\u0561\u057e\u0578\u0580 \u056f\u056b\u056c\u0578\u0574\u0565\u057f\u0580\u0565\u0580 \u0570\u0565\u057c\u0578\u0582 \u0574\u056b \u0583\u0578\u0584\u0580 \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576 \u0567 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121035916/http://tert.nla.am/archive/HGG%20AMSAGIR/echmiadzin-vagharshapat/2008/2008%285%29.pdf |archivedate=January 21, 2015 }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote in 1919: \"The island of San Lazzaro, near Venice, has been for over two centuries an Armenian oasis transplanted in the Venetian lagoons.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Armenians Desirous of a United Country|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9807E3DF1E39E13ABC4E53DFB5668382609EDE&legacy=true|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=6 March 1919}}</ref> It is one of the richest [[List of Armenian ethnic enclaves|Armenian enclaves]],<ref name=\"Komitas\"/> and, according to sociologist Anny  Bakalian, one of the best-known Armenian sites in the world, along with the [[Armenian Quarter]] of Jerusalem's Old City.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bakalian|first=Anny|title=Armenian Americans: From Being to Feeling Armenian|year=1993|publisher=Transaction Publishers|location=New Brunswick, New Jersey|isbn=978-1-56000-025-9|pp=345\u2013346}}</ref> [[William Dean Howells]] noted in 1866 that \"As a seat of learning, San Lazzaro is famed throughout the Armenian world.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Howells|first=William Dean|authorlink=William Dean Howells|title=Venetian Life|date=1907|orig-year=1866|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]]|location=Boston and New York|page=[https://archive.org/details/venetianlife00howegoog/page/n216 <!-- quote=san lazzaro. --> 180]}}</ref> ''The Oxford Dictionary of the Christian Church'' calls the convent of San Lazzaro and the order of the Mechitarists \"especially remarkable\" of the religious orders based in Venice.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Cross|editor1-first=F. L.|editor2-last=Livingstone|editor2-first=E. A.|title=The Oxford Dictionary of the Christian Church|contribution=Venice|date=2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-280290-3|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=fUqcAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1699&dq=of+the+many+religious+orders+that+have+houses+in+venice+the+armenian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Q3fBVI-VB8qzggTFgoHwBQ&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=of%20the%20many%20religious%20orders%20that%20have%20houses%20in%20venice%20the%20armenian&f=false 1699]|edition=3rd|orig-year=1957|quote=Of the many religious orders that have houses in Venice the Armenian Benedictine Congregation of the Mechitarists is esp. remarkable; their convent on the island of San Lazzaro is a centre of Armenian education.}}</ref> American Protestant missionary [[Eli Smith]] noted in 1833 that the convent of San Lazzaro not only did not pursue the \"denationalizing system of many of the Romish missions among the oriental churches,\" but also has done \"more than all other Armenians together, to cultivate and enrich the literature of the nation.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Eli|authorlink1=Eli Smith|title=Researches of the Rev. E. Smith and Rev. H.G.O. Dwight in Armenia: Including a Journey Through Asia Minor, and Into Georgia and Persia, with a Visit to the Nestorian and Chaldean Christians of Oormiah and Salmas, Volume 1|date=1833|publisher=[[Crocker & Brewster]]|location=Boston|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=POgTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA256&dq=armenian+convent+venice 256\u2013257]}}</ref> Travel writer [[Louisa Stuart Costello]] called the Armenian convent of San Lazzaro \"a respectable pile, above the encircling waters, an enduring monument of successful perseverance in a good cause.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Costello|first1=Louisa Stuart|authorlink1=Louisa Stuart Costello|title=A Tour to and from Venice, by the Vaudois and the Tyrol|date=1846|publisher=[[John Ollivier]]|location=London|page=[https://archive.org/details/atourtoandfromv00costgoog/page/n333 <!-- quote=armenian convent venice. --> 317]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Khatchkar San Lazzaro degli Armeni.jpg|thumb|A 14th century ''khachkar'' at San Lazzaro]]\n\n===Cultural awakening ===\nAccording to [[Robert H. Hewsen]] for nearly a century\u2014until the establishment of the [[Lazarev Institute of Oriental Languages|Lazarev Institute]] in Moscow in 1815\u2014the monastery of San Lazzaro was the only center of intensive Armenian cultural activity that held the heritage of the Armenian people.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hewsen|first=Robert H.|authorlink=Robert H. Hewsen|title=Armenia: A Historical Atlas|publisher=University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago|year=2001|isbn=978-0-226-33228-4|pp=12, 158}}</ref> During the 18th century, the rediscovery of [[classical Armenian]] literature and the creation of an Armenian vernacular by the Mechitarists of San Lazzaro was a key factor in the \"[[Armenian Renaissance]].\"{{sfn|Sarkiss|1937|p=441}} Italian scholar Matteo Miele compared the work of the Mekhitarists carried out in the island to the work of the humanists, painters and sculptors of the [[Italian Renaissance]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Miele|first1=Matteo|title=L'isola degli Armeni a Venezia|url=http://www.ilpost.it/2015/10/16/san-lazzaro-degli-armeni-a-venezia/|work=[[Il Post]]|date=16 October 2015|language=it|quote=Lontani, quasi appartati, hanno prodotto, per il proprio popolo, una rinascita artistica, letteraria e sociale in qualche modo paragonabile all'opera dei grandi umanisti, pittori e scultori del Rinascimento italiano.}}</ref> For over a century the monastery of San Lazzaro became the \"potent agency for the advancement of secular, as well as of religious, knowledge\" with \"avowed religious, educational, and literary objectives like those of the medieval Benedictine order.\"{{sfn|Sarkiss|1937|p=443}}\n\n;National consciousness and nationalism \nThe activities of the island monastery, which became a center for [[Armenian studies]], led to a revival of Armenian [[national consciousness]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Dursteler|first=Eric R.|title=A Companion to Venetian History, 1400\u20131797|year=2013|publisher=[[Brill Publishers]]|isbn=978-90-04-25251-6|page=459|quote=...&nbsp;the island of San Lazzaro on which he established a monastery that became a center for Armenian studies and led to a revival of Armenian consciousness.}}</ref> According to Harry Jewell Sarkiss the emphasis Mekhitarists of San Lazzaro put on \"their national history and language was significant, for thereby they planted the seeds\" of modern [[Armenian nationalism]].{{sfn|Sarkiss|1937|p=443}} [[Elizabeth Redgate]] writes that the developments in intellectual culture and scholarship in [[Russian Armenia]] and at the Mkhitarist monasteries of San Lazzaro and [[Mekhitarist Monastery of Vienna|Vienna]] inspired an increased nationalism among Armenians in the 1880s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Redgate|first=A. E.|authorlink=Elizabeth Redgate|title=The Armenians|year=2000|publisher=[[Wiley-Blackwell|Blackwell Publishing]]|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-631-22037-4|p=[https://archive.org/details/armenianspeoples00aere/page/268 268]|url=https://archive.org/details/armenianspeoples00aere/page/268}}</ref> Mary Tarzian suggests that nationalism among Armenians in the Ottoman Empire emerged from the educational vision of the Mechitarists in San Lazzaro.<ref>{{cite book|last=Terzian|first=Shelley|editor1-last=Wolhuter|editor1-first=Charl|editor2-last=de Wet|editor2-first=Corene|title=International Comparative Perspectives on Religion and Education|contribution=Central effects of religious education in Armenia from Ancient Times to Post-Soviet Armenia|date=2014|publisher=SUN MeDIA|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=y4_4AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA37&dq=san+lazzaro+Armeni+venice 37]}}</ref> This view was expressed as early as 1877 when [[Charles Yriarte]] wrote that the Armenians \"look with justice upon the island of San Lazzaro as the torch which shall one day illuminate Armenia, when the hour comes for her to live again in history and to take her place once more among free nations.\"{{sfn|Yriarte|1880|p=302}}\n\nHowever, their activities were not without criticism. [[Mikael Nalbandian]], a liberal and anti-clerical Russian-Armenian writer, wrote in the mid-19th century that the \"enlightenment of our nation must proceed from the hands of execrable papist monks! Their 'light' is far more pernicious than darkness.\"{{sfn|Suny|1993|p=61}}\n\n==Notable resident scholars==\n{| \n| [[File:Portrait de Pierre M\u00e9khitar (Saint Lazare des Arm\u00e9niens, Venise) (5182840694)(crop).jpg|75px]]\n| [[Mkhitar Sebastatsi]] (1676\u20131749) was the founder of the Mechitarist Order. He resided in the island from the time of the settlement of his congregation in 1717 until his death. He set the foundations of modern philological studies of the Armenian language by publishing books on grammar and dictionaries.{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=xlv}} He published some 20 works, mostly on the subjects of theology and philosophy, including an Armenian edition of the Bible (1733), a commentary on the [[Gospel of Matthew]] (1737), Armenian grammar, dictionary, and catechism.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=El-Hayek|first=E.|encyclopedia=[[New Catholic Encyclopedia]]|title=Mechitar|date=2003|publisher=Thomson/Gale|isbn=9780787640040|page=421|edition=9th|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/mechitar}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Mikayel Chamchian.jpg|75px]]\n| [[Mikayel Chamchian]] (1738\u20131823) was a historian who lived in the island from 1757 until his death.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Utudjian|first=A. A.|title=\u0544\u056b\u0584\u0561\u0575\u0565\u056c \u0549\u0561\u0574\u0579\u0575\u0561\u0576 (\u056f\u0575\u0561\u0576\u0584\u056b \u0587 \u0563\u0578\u0580\u056e\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0565\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0570\u0561\u0574\u0561\u057c\u0578\u057f \u0578\u0582\u0580\u057e\u0561\u0563\u056b\u056e) [Michael Chamchian (a short description of his life and  activity)]|journal=[[Lraber Hasarakakan Gitutyunneri]]|volume=\u2116 9|date=1988|issue=9|pages=71\u201385|url=http://lraber.asj-oa.am/4161/}}</ref> He authored the first modern history of Armenia, in three volumes (1781\u201386).{{sfn|Suny|1993|pp=57, 252}} It is a comprehensive and influential publication which was used as a reference work by scholars for over a century.  According to Hacikyan et al. it is a \"great achievement in Armenian historiography judging by the criteria of his own time.\"{{sfn|Hacikyan|Basmajian|Franchuk|Ouzounian|2005|p=53}} \n|-\n| [[File:Gabriel Aivazovsky.jpg|75px]]\n| [[Gabriel Aivazovsky]] (1812\u20131880), a philologist, historian and publisher, whose younger brother, [[Ivan Aivazovsky|Ivan (Hovhannes) Aivazovsky]], was a famed Russian seascape artist. He studied at the island school from 1826 to 1830 and was later the secretary of the Mekhitarian congregation. He founded and edited the San Lazzaro-based journal ''[[Bazmavep]]'' from 1843 to 1848.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mikayelyan|first=V.|title=\u0531\u0575\u057e\u0561\u0566\u0578\u057e\u057d\u056f\u056b \u0533\u0561\u0562\u0580\u056b\u0565\u056c [Aivazovsky Gabriel]|url=http://www.armenianreligion.am/am/Encyclopedia_ayvazovski_gabriel|publisher=[[Yerevan State University]] Institute for Armenian Studies|language=hy|date=2002}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Alishan in his last days 1901.png|75px]]\n| [[Ghevont Alishan]] (1820\u20131901), a prominent historian, was a member of the Mechitarist Order since 1838. In 1849\u201351 he edited the journal ''[[Bazmavep]]'' and taught at the monastic seminary in 1866\u201372.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Asmarian|first=H. A.|title=\u0542\u0587\u0578\u0576\u0564 \u0531\u056c\u056b\u0577\u0561\u0576\u056b \u0573\u0561\u0576\u0561\u057a\u0561\u0580\u0570\u0578\u0580\u0564\u0561\u056f\u0561\u0576 \u0576\u0578\u0569\u0565\u0580\u056b\u0581 [From Ghevond Alishan's travel notes]|journal=[[Lraber Hasarakakan Gitutyunneri]]|volume=\u2116 2|date=2003|issue=2|pages=127\u2013135|url=http://lraber.asj-oa.am/13/|language=hy}}</ref> He lived in the island permanently from 1872 until his death in 1901.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Shtikian|first=S. A.|title=\u0542\u0587\u0578\u0576\u0564 \u0531\u056c\u056b\u0577\u0561\u0576 [Ghevond Alishan]|journal=[[Patma-Banasirakan Handes]]|volume=\u2116 2|date=1970|issue=2|pages=13\u201326|url=http://hpj.asj-oa.am/1490/|language=hy}}</ref> He authored books on the history and geography of Armenians regions of [[Shirak Province|Shirak]], [[Ayrarat]], [[Syunik (historic province)|Sisakan]] (all published in 1881\u201383) with \"amazing accuracy.\" In 1895 he published two notable works, one on pre-Christian [[Armenian mythology|polytheistic religion of Armenians]] and a study on 3,400 species of plants that grow in Armenia.{{sfn|Hacikyan|Basmajian|Franchuk|Ouzounian|2005|p=54}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notable visitors==\nA wide range of notable individuals have visited the island through centuries.\n\n===Lord Byron===\n[[File:Aivazovsky Byron San Lazzaro.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Lord Byron]]'s visit to the island as pictured by [[Ivan Aivazovsky]], 1899, [[National Gallery of Armenia]]<ref name=\"Aivazovsky Byron\"/>]]\n\nEnglish Romantic poet [[Lord Byron]] visited the island from November 1816 to February 1817.{{sfn|Mesrobian|1973|p=27}}{{sfn|Gordan|2012}} He acquired enough Armenian to translate passages from [[Classical Armenian]] into English.{{sfn|Mesrobian|1973|p=31}} He co-authored ''English Grammar and Armenian'' in 1817, and ''Armenian Grammar and English'' in 1819, where he included quotations from classical and modern Armenian.<ref>{{cite book|last=Elze|first=Karl|authorlink=Karl Elze|title=Lord Byron, a biography, with a critical essay on his place in literature|date=1872|publisher=J. Murray|location=London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/lordbyronabiogr00elzegoog <!-- quote=armenian. --> 217\u2013218]}}</ref> The room where Byron studied now bears his name and is cherished by the monks.<ref name=\"Garrett\"/>{{sfn|Saryan|2011|p=2}} There is also a plaque commemorating Byron's stay.<ref name=\"Carswell\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Vangelista|first1=Massimo|title=Lord Byron in the Armenian Monastery in Venice|url=http://byronico.com/2013/09/04/lord-byron-in-the-armenian-monastery-in-venice/|website=byronico.com|date=4 September 2013}}</ref> Byron is considered the most prominent of all visitors of the island.{{sfn|Gordan|2012}}{{sfn|Seferian|2017}}{{sfn|Saryan|2011|p=2}} [[Jan Morris|James Morris]] wrote that \"many people in Venice, asked to think of San Lazzaro, think first of Byron, and only secondly of the Armenians. Byron's spirit haunts the island.\"{{sfn|Morris|1960|p=294}}\n\n===Foreigners===\n[[Pope Pius VII]] visited the island on May 9, 1800.<ref name=\"Napoleon\"/> Since the 19th century numerous notable individuals visited San Lazzaro, such as composers [[Jacques Offenbach]],<ref name=\"newarmenia\"/> [[Gioachino Rossini]],<ref name=\"newarmenia\"/> [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky]],{{sfn|Kolupaev|2011}} and [[Richard Wagner]] (1859),<ref>{{cite book|last1=Barker|first1=John W.|title=Wagner and Venice|date=2008|publisher=University of Rochester Press|isbn=978-1-58046-288-4|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=oo5GA12YkEcC&pg=PA111 111]}}</ref> writers [[Alfred de Musset]] and [[George Sand]] (1834),<ref>{{cite book|last1=de Musset|first1=Alfred|authorlink1=Alfred de Musset|title=Oeuvres, Volume 7|date=1867|publisher=Charpentier|location=Paris|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=0q0WAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA246 246]|language=fr|quote=Apr\u00e8s le repas, ils montaient en gondole, et s'en allaient voguer autour de l'\u00eele des Arm\u00e9niens&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Winegarten|first1=Renee|title=The double life of George Sand, woman and writer: a critical biography|date=1978|publisher=Basic Books|page=[https://archive.org/details/doublelifeofgeor00wine/page/134 134]|url=https://archive.org/details/doublelifeofgeor00wine|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Sand|first1=George|authorlink1=George Sand|title=\u0152uvres de George Sand: Un hiver au midi de l'Europe|contribution=Venise, juillet 1834.|date=1844|publisher=Perrotin|location=Paris|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=JwktAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=nous+arrivames+a+l%27ile+de+saint-lazare 95]|language=fr|quote=Nous arriv\u00e2mes \u00e0 l'\u00eele de Saint-Lazare, o\u00f9 nous avions une visite \u00e0 faire aux moines arm\u00e9niens.}}</ref> [[Marcel Proust]] (1900),<ref>{{cite book|last1=Plant|first1=Margaret|title=Venice: fragile city 1797\u20131977|date=2002|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven, Conn.|isbn=978-0-300-08386-6|page=225|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NXu2DSxhEU4C}}</ref> [[Ivan Turgenev]],{{sfn|Kolupaev|2011}} [[Nikolai Gogol]],{{sfn|Kolupaev|2011}} [[Henry Wadsworth Longfellow]],{{sfn|Gordan|2012}} British art critic [[John Ruskin]] (early 1850s),<ref>{{cite book|last=Cook|first=Edward Tyas|authorlink=Edward Tyas Cook|title=Homes and Haunts of John Ruskin|date=1912|publisher=Macmillan|location=New York|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=U8sKAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA111&dq=John+Ruskin+san+lazzaro+armenian 111\u2013112]}}</ref> and French historian [[Ernest Renan]] (1850).<ref name=\"newarmenia\"/>\n\nDuring the 19th century numerous monarchs visited the island, including [[Charles IV of Spain]], [[Franz Joseph I of Austria]], [[Umberto I of Italy]], [[Charles I of Romania]], [[Emma of Waldeck and Pyrmont]], [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands]],<ref name=\"newarmenia\"/> [[Prince Napol\u00e9on Bonaparte]],<ref name=wade>{{cite book|last1=Howe|first1=Julia Ward|title=From the Oak to the Olive: A Plain Record of a Pleasant Journey|date=1868|publisher=Library of Alexandria|isbn=978-1-4655-1372-4|url=https://archive.org/details/fromoaktoolivea01howegoog|page=[https://archive.org/details/fromoaktoolivea01howegoog/page/n155 142]}}</ref> [[Ludwig I of Bavaria]], (1841),<ref>{{cite book|title=Das Armenische Kloster auf der Insel S. Lazzaro bei Venedig|date=1864|publisher=Armenische Druckerei|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gt5ZAAAAcAAJ|language=German}}</ref> [[Margherita of Savoy]],{{sfn|Issaverdenz|1890|pp=16-18}} [[Maximilian I of Mexico]],{{sfn|Issaverdenz|1890|pp=16-18}} [[Carlota of Mexico]],{{sfn|Issaverdenz|1890|pp=16-18}} [[Edward VII]], [[Prince of Wales]] and future British king (1861),{{sfn|Issaverdenz|1890|pp=16-18}} [[Napoleon III]] (1862),{{sfn|Issaverdenz|1890|pp=16-18}} [[Pedro II of Brazil]] (1871),{{sfn|Issaverdenz|1890|pp=16-18}} [[Princess Louise, Duchess of Argyll]] (1881),{{sfn|Issaverdenz|1890|pp=16-18}} [[Alexander I of Russia]].<ref name=\"newarmenia\"/> U.S. President [[Ulysses S. Grant]] and British Prime Minister [[William Gladstone]] visited San Lazzaro in 1878 and 1879, respectively.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Grant|first1=Julia Dent|editor1-last=Simon|editor1-first=John Y.|title=The personal memoirs of Julia Dent Grant (Mrs. Ulysses S. Grant)|date=1988|publisher=Southern Illinois University Press|page=243|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o38fAQAAMAAJ|isbn=9780809314423}}</ref><ref name=lucas>{{cite book|last1=Lucas|first1=Edward Verrall|title=A Wanderer in Venice|date=1914|publisher=The Macmillan Company|page=[https://archive.org/details/awandererinveni01lucagoog/page/n461 302]|url=https://archive.org/details/awandererinveni01lucagoog}}</ref>\n\nSoviet leader [[Joseph Stalin]], a Bolshevik revolutionary at the time, worked as a bell-ringer at the monastery of San Lazzaro in 1907.<ref>{{cite journal|title=When Stalin in Venice&nbsp;... |journal=Venice Magazine |page=7 |url=http://www.venicemagazine.it/DOCPDF/stalin.pdf |quote=Josif Stalin, the Russian dictator, was one of the last bell-ringers of the island of San Lazzaro degli Armeni, located at the heart of the lagoon. He stowed away in the port of Odessa to escape from tsarist police and arrived in Venice in 1907. |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713152115/http://www.venicemagazine.it/DOCPDF/stalin.pdf |archivedate=2016-07-13 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Salinari|first1=Raffaele K.|title=Stalin in Italia ovvero \"Bepi del giasso\"|date=2010|location=Bologna|isbn=978-88-96691-01-4|publisher=Ogni uomo \u00e8 tutti gli uomini Edizioni|url=https://www.carmillaonline.com/2010/09/19/raffaele-k-salinari-stalin-in-italia/|language=it|quote=Qui forse trov\u00f2 alloggio nel convento adiacente alla chiesa di San Lazzaro degli Armeni, sita su un'isoletta al largo della citt\u00e0.}}</ref><ref>An interview with Russian artist [[:ru:\u0411\u0438\u043b\u044c\u0436\u043e, \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447|Andrey Bilzho]]. {{cite news|last1=Gordon|first1=Dmitry|authorlink1=Dmitry Gordon|title=\u041a\u0430\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442 \u0411\u0438\u043b\u044c\u0436\u043e: \u0421\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0432 \u0410\u0440\u043c\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043c\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044b\u0440\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435 \u0421\u0432. \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u044f, \u0430 \u043f\u043e \u043d\u043e\u0447\u0430\u043c \u0443\u0431\u0435\u0433\u0430\u043b \u0432 \u0412\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0446\u0438\u044e, \u0433\u0434\u0435 \u043f\u0438\u043b \u0438 \u0442\u0440&nbsp;... \u0445\u0430\u043b\u0441\u044f|url=http://gordonua.com/news/worldnews/karikaturist-bilzho-stalin-rabotal-v-armyanskom-monastyre-na-ostrove-sv-lazarya-a-po-nocham-ubegal-v-veneciyu-gde-pil-i-trhalsya-122889.html|work=gordonua.com|date=5 March 2016|language=ru|quote=...&nbsp;\u042d\u0442\u0430 \u0441&nbsp;... \u043a\u0430 \u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u0437\u0432\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0440\u0435\u043c \u0432 \u0410\u0440\u043c\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044b\u0440\u044c \u043d\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u044f&nbsp;...}}</ref>\n\n===Armenians===\nRussian-Armenian marine painter [[Ivan Aivazovsky]] visited San Lazzaro in 1840. He met his older brother, [[Gabriel Aivazovsky|Gabriel]], who was working at the monastery at that time. At the monastery library and the art gallery Aivazovsky familiarized himself with Armenian manuscripts and Armenian art in general.<ref>{{cite web|last=Khachatrian|first=Shahen|title=\"\u041f\u043e\u044d\u0442 \u043c\u043e\u0440\u044f\" [\"The Sea Poet\"]|url=http://www.smr.ru/centre/win/artists/aivaz/biogr_aivaz.htm|publisher=Center of Spiritual Culture, [[:ru:\u0421\u0430\u043c\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0430\u044d\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442|Leading and National Research Samara State Aerospace University]]|authorlink=Shahen Khachatrian|language=ru}}</ref> Another Armenian painter, [[Vardges Sureniants]], visited San Lazzaro in 1881 and researched [[Armenian illuminated manuscripts|Armenian]] [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniatures]].<ref>{{citation|last=Adamyan |first=A. |year=2012 |title=\u054e\u0561\u0580\u0564\u0563\u0565\u057d \u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0565\u0576\u0575\u0561\u0576\u0581 [Vardges Sureniants] |url=http://nla.am/arm/doc/SUREN.pdf |publisher=[[National Library of Armenia]] |language=hy |p=7 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304094445/http://nla.am/arm/doc/SUREN.pdf |archivedate=2016-03-04 }}</ref> Ethnographer [[Yervand Lalayan]] worked at the island for around six months in 1894.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Melik-Pashayan|first1=K.|title=Soviet Armenian Encyclopedia Volume 4|contribution=\u053c\u0561\u056c\u0561\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0535\u0580\u057e\u0561\u0576\u0564 [Lalayan Yervand]|date=1978|page=475|language=hy|title-link=Soviet Armenian Encyclopedia}}</ref> Musicologist [[Komitas]] lectured on Armenian folk and sacred music and researched the Armenian music notation (''[[khaz (notation)|khaz]]'') system in the monastery library in July 1907.<ref name=\"Komitas\">{{cite book|last=Soulahian Kuyumjian|first=Rita|title=Archeology of Madness: Komitas, Portrait of an Armenian Icon|year=2001|publisher=[[Gomidas Institute]]|location=Princeton, New Jersey|isbn=978-1-903656-10-5|p=59}}</ref> The first meeting of poets [[Yeghishe Charents]] and [[Avetik Isahakyan]] took place in San Lazzaro in 1924.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u053b\u057d\u0561\u0570\u0561\u056f\u0575\u0561\u0576\u056b \u0587 \u0549\u0561\u0580\u0565\u0576\u0581\u056b \u0561\u057c\u0561\u057b\u056b\u0576 \u0570\u0561\u0576\u0564\u056b\u057a\u0578\u0582\u0574\u0568 \u054e\u0565\u0576\u0565\u057f\u056b\u056f\u0578\u0582\u0574 [First meeting of Isahakyan and Charents in Venice]|url=http://www.magaghat.am/2013/10/%D5%AB%D5%BD%D5%A1%D5%B0%D5%A1%D5%AF%D5%B5%D5%A1%D5%B6%D5%AB-%D6%87-%D5%B9%D5%A1%D6%80%D5%A5%D5%B6%D6%81%D5%AB-%D5%BE%D5%A5%D5%B6%D5%A5%D5%BF%D5%AB%D5%AF%D5%B5%D5%A1%D5%B6-%D5%A1%D5%BC%D5%A1%D5%BB/|website=magaghat.am|language=hy|quote=\u0544\u0565\u056e\u0561\u057f\u0561\u0572\u0561\u0576\u0564 \u0562\u0561\u0576\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0565\u0572\u056e \u0535\u0572\u056b\u0577\u0565 \u0549\u0561\u0580\u0565\u0576\u0581\u056b\u0576 \u0561\u057c\u0561\u057b\u056b\u0576 \u0561\u0576\u0563\u0561\u0574 \u057f\u0565\u057d\u0561 \u054e\u0565\u0576\u0565\u057f\u056b\u056f\u0578\u0582\u0574, 1924 \u0569\u057e\u0561\u056f\u0561\u0576\u056b\u0576:&nbsp;... \u0533\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0574 \u0567\u056b\u0576\u0584 \u056e\u0578\u057e\u0561\u0583, \u0570\u0565\u057f\u0578 \u0563\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0574 \u0567\u056b\u0576\u0584 \u0544\u056d\u056b\u0569\u0561\u0580\u0575\u0561\u0576\u0576\u0565\u0580\u056b \u057e\u0561\u0576\u0584\u0568` \u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580:}}</ref> Soviet Armenian composer [[Aram Khachaturian]] visited it in 1963,<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0556\u0578\u057f\u0578\u0561\u056c\u0562\u0578\u0574 [Photo gallery]|url=http://www.akhic.am/hy/gallery/view/6|website=akhic.am|publisher=Aram Khachaturian International Competition|language=hy|quote=\u0531.\u053d\u0561\u0579\u0561\u057f\u0580\u0575\u0561\u0576\u0568 \u0544\u056d\u056b\u0569\u0561\u0580\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0574\u056b\u0561\u0562\u0561\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0574 \u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580 \u056f\u0572\u0566\u056b 1963|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140913081842/http://www.akhic.am/hy/gallery/view/6|archivedate=2014-09-13}}</ref> and Soviet Armenian astrophysicist [[Victor Ambartsumian]] in 1969.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rosino|first1=Leonida|authorlink1=:it:Leonida Rosino|title=Encounters with Victor Ambartsumian one afternoon at the San Lazzaro Degli Armeni island at Venice|journal=[[Astrophysics (journal)|Astrophysics]]|date=1988|volume=29|issue=1|pages=412\u2013414|doi=10.1007/BF01005854}}</ref>\n\nAt least two [[Catholicos of All Armenians|catholicoi]] (leaders) of the Armenian Apostolic Church\u2014which was historically a rival of the Armenian Catholic Church, which the Mekhitarists are a part of{{sfn|Saryan|2011|p=2}}\u2014have visited the island: [[Vazgen I]] (in 1958<ref>http://echmiadzin.asj-oa.am/3638/</ref> and 1970)<ref>http://echmiadzin.asj-oa.am/7689/</ref> and [[Karekin II]] (in 2008).<ref>{{cite news|title=Catholicos Concludes Vatican Visit|url=http://asbarez.com/57250/catholicos-concludes-vatican-visit/|work=[[Asbarez]]|date=13 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nSince independence in 1991 at least three presidents of Armenia\u2014[[Robert Kocharyan]] in 2005, [[Serzh Sargsyan]] in 2011, and [[Armen Sarkissian]] (with his wife [[Nouneh Sarkissian]]) in 2019\u2014visited San Lazzaro.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=hy:\u0540\u0540 \u0576\u0561\u056d\u0561\u0563\u0561\u0570 \u054c\u0578\u0562\u0565\u0580\u057f \u0554\u0578\u0579\u0561\u0580\u0575\u0561\u0576\u0568 \u057a\u0561\u0577\u057f\u0578\u0576\u0561\u056f\u0561\u0576 \u0561\u0575\u0581\u0578\u057e \u056f\u0574\u0565\u056f\u0576\u056b \u053b\u057f\u0561\u056c\u056b\u0561 [President of Armenia Robert Kocharyan will visit Italy]|url=https://armenpress.am/arm/news/114770|publisher=[[Armenpress]]|date=25 January 2005|language=hy}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=President Serzh Sargsyan visited the Mkhitarian Congregation at the St. Lazarus Island in Venice|url=http://www.president.am/en/press-release/item/2011/12/14/news-1943/|work=president.am|publisher=Office to the President of the Republic of Armenia|date=14 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Armenian President and First Lady visit Mekhitarist monks in San Lazzaro, Italy |url=https://armenpress.am/eng/news/977021.html |agency=[[Armenpress]] |date=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Henrikh Mkhitaryan]], an [[Armenia national football team|Armenia]] international football player, married Betty Vardanyan at the monastery of San Lazzaro on June 17, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mkhitaryan Ties the Knot |url=http://asbarez.com/181689/mkhitaryan-ties-the-knot/ |work=[[Asbarez]] |date=17 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u201cMarry me and stay with me forever\u201d: Henrikh Mkhitaryan marries fianc\u00e9e Betty Vardanyan |url=https://sport.mediamax.am/en/news/football/33890 |work=mediamax.am |date=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Artistic depictions==\nNumerous artists have painted the island, including \n*''[[:File:Vignette of the Isola di S. Lazzaro degli Armeni.jpg|Vignette of the Isola di S. Lazzaro degli Armeni]]'' by [[Antonio Visentini]] (d. 1782, undated), [[Royal Collection]], [[Windsor Castle]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Vignette of the Isola di S. Lazzaro degli Armeni|url=https://www.royalcollection.org.uk/collection/907612/vignette-of-the-isola-di-s-lazzaro-degli-armeni|publisher=[[Royal Collection]]}}</ref> \n*''[[:File:Basjinjaghian Surb Ghazar.png|Island of Surb Ghazar at night]]'' by [[Gevorg Bashinjaghian]] (1892), [[National Gallery of Armenia]]<ref name=\"Bashinjaghian\">{{cite web|title=\u054d\u0562. \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580 \u056f\u0572\u0566\u056b\u0576 \u0563\u056b\u0577\u0565\u0580\u0578\u057e (1892)|url=http://www.gallery.am/hy/database/item/15/|publisher=[[National Gallery of Armenia]]|language=hy}}</ref> \n*''[[:File:Bayron's visit to San Lazzaro by Aivazovsky (1899).jpg|Byron's visit to the Mekhitarists in Surb Ghazar Island]]'' by [[Ivan Aivazovsky]] (1899), National Gallery of Armenia<ref name=\"Aivazovsky Byron\">{{cite web|title=\u0532\u0561\u0575\u0580\u0578\u0576\u056b \u0561\u0575\u0581\u0568 \u0544\u056d\u056b\u0569\u0561\u0580\u0575\u0561\u0576\u0576\u0565\u0580\u056b\u0576 \u054d\u0562. \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580 \u056f\u0572\u0566\u0578\u0582\u0574 (1899)|url=http://www.gallery.am/hy/database-egov/item/298/|publisher=[[National Gallery of Armenia]]|language=hy}}</ref> \n*''[[:File:San Lazzaro degli Armeni ca. 1905.jpg|The Armenian Convent]]'' by [[Joseph Pennell]] (1905), [[Library of Congress]] Prints and Photographs Division<ref>{{cite web|last=Pennell|first=Joseph|authorlink=Joseph Pennell|title=The Armenian convent|url=https://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/2007665302/|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|year=1905}}</ref> \n*''Sb. Ghazar island, Venice'' by [[Hovhannes Zardaryan]] (1958), National Gallery of Armenia<ref>{{cite web|title=\u054d\u0562 \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580\u056b \u056f\u0572\u0566\u056b\u0576. \u054e\u0565\u0576\u0565\u057f\u056b\u056f (1958)|url=http://www.gallery.am/hy/database/item/3724/|publisher=[[National Gallery of Armenia]]|language=hy}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mekhitarist Monastery, Vienna]]\n*[[Armenians in Italy]]\n*[[List of Armenian ethnic enclaves]]\n*[[Santa Croce degli Armeni]]\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|3|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"sae\">{{cite book|title=Soviet Armenian Encyclopedia Volume 11|contribution=\u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580 [Surb Ghazar]|date=1985|location=Yerevan|pages=[https://hy.wikisource.org/wiki/%D4%B7%D5%BB:%D5%80%D5%A1%D5%B5%D5%AF%D5%A1%D5%AF%D5%A1%D5%B6_%D5%8D%D5%B8%D5%BE%D5%A5%D5%BF%D5%A1%D5%AF%D5%A1%D5%B6_%D5%80%D5%A1%D5%B6%D6%80%D5%A1%D5%A3%D5%AB%D5%BF%D5%A1%D6%80%D5%A1%D5%B6_(Soviet_Armenian_Encyclopedia)_11.djvu/203 203\u2013204]|language=hy|title-link=Soviet Armenian Encyclopedia}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"mechitar.com\">{{cite web|title=The Island of San Lazzaro|url=http://mechitar.com/island/index.php?iM=6|website=mechitar.com|publisher=[[Mekhitarists|Armenian Mekhitarist Congregation]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121000308/http://mechitar.com/island/index.php?iM=6|archivedate=21 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Mathews\">{{cite book|first=Edward G.|last=Mathews, Jr.|editor1-last=Johnston|editor1-first=Will M.|editor1-link=Will Johnston|title=Encyclopedia of Monasticism: A-L|contribution=Armenia|date=2000|publisher=[[Fitzroy Dearborn Publishers]]|location=Chicago and London|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=GfC0TDkJJNgC&pg=PA87&lpg=PA87&dq=the+monastery+in+venice+produced+hundreds+armenian&source=bl&ots=uNBmzCEBIH&sig=5UdazGlXHrXvU3UgBClBDWe1-lU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=TnnBVLCYBLDgsATG5IHYDg&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=the%20monastery%20in%20venice%20produced%20hundreds%20armenian&f=false 8